(1) 150 Amersfort Place, west side, between East 28th Street and Glenwood Road, showing the George Van Nuyse farmhouse. 1922. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, showing on the right, No. 2704 Glenwood Road. March 1925. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3) The same, showing a more extensive view. Albert Van Brunt moved into the house on Glenwood Road. Old Flatbush Turnpike Road became Amersfort Place at this point. March 1925. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4) The same, showing on the extremright, No. 122 Amersfort Place. March 1925. Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(1) 150 Amersfort Place, north from Germania Place to Glenwood Road, showing the George Van Nuyse farmhouse; which was erected by him in 1827. It was renovated in 1925. Other occupants or owners were J.H. Van Brunt (1860-1873); J.C. Ryder (1873); and Andrew Ditmars.

1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same; in the background may be seen a rear view of a group of homes facing East 26th Street.

March 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3) The same, prior to rehabilitation.

May 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4) The same, renovated. The stone appearing in the foreground, is probably to be used for the paving of East 28th Street.

August 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
